end to end tests compare against custom c code, not exo generated c code, comparing the two backends.

memref doesnt support strides (see examples/window_roundtrip.py)

---

malloc size is in elements, not bytes

    rewrites.py:277 — ConvertAllocOp passes num_elements to malloc instead of
    num_elements * sizeof(element_type). For f32[16,16] this allocates 256 bytes
    instead of 1024. The downstream ptr arithmetic correctly scales by
    bytes_per_element, so loads/stores go out-of-bounds.

    The alloc_free.py test doesn't catch this because it only allocates a scalar
    (1 element at offset 0).

    Fix: multiply by element size before calling malloc.


mm256_loadu_ps stores to source instead of destination

    rewrites.py:235 — _build_mm256_loadu_ps stores back to args[1] (source).
    Every other mm256 builder stores to args[0] (destination).

        def _build_mm256_loadu_ps(args):
            ...
            return (zero, load, llvm.StoreOp(load.dereferenced_value, args[1], ...))
            #                                                         ^^ should be args[0]


type mismatch in _mask_f64x4

    rewrites.py:38-42 — indices are vector<4xi64> but broadcast is vector<4xi32>.
    The ICmpOp compares mismatched types.

    _mask_f64x4_ext handles this correctly by extending m to i64 first.
    _mask_f64x4 skips the extension.

        indices = ... VectorType(i64, [4]) ...
        broadcast = vector.BroadcastOp(..., result_types=[VectorType(i32, [4])])  # should be i64
        mask = llvm.ICmpOp(indices.result, broadcast.vector, ...)  # i64 vs i32


